Wait, actually, $\Sigma_{k+1}^P = \{ L \mid L \text{ is in } NP^{\Sigma_k^P} \}$

If $\Sigma_k^P = P$, then $\Sigma_{k+1}^P = NP^P = NP$

But we need to show $\Sigma_{k+1}^P = P$.

Wait, this approach is not sufficient. We need to use the fact that $P = NP$.

Wait, if $P = NP$, then $\Sigma_k^P = P$ for all $k$:

- Base case: $\Sigma_0^P = P$
