The key insight here is that once `P = NP` is assumed, all the complexity classes `SigmakP`, `PikP`, etc., eventually reduce to `InP` because `P = NP` implies that any problem decidable in polynomial time with an NP oracle is also decidable in polynomial time. The `simp` tactic is powerful enough to resolve this equivalence once `P = NP` is given, because all the definitions eventually relate back to `InP` when `P = NP` is assumed.
